column168: GATX 44059 was observed to be leaking around the bottom outlet valve cap during an inspection by FRA and TX DOT Haz Mat Inspectors at 1225 hours. Absorbent pads were placed beneath the valve to collect product until response team could arrive. Consignee was notified account car was shipped from Mexico. Oxy Vinyls Strike Team arrived on scene at 1515 hours and determined that the top operated bottom outlet valve was not completely closed after unloading allowing a small amount of product to bypass the valve and collect in the space between the valve and valve cap. The valve cap was not closed properly (loose) and was allowing product to leak to ground. Oxy Strike team collected leaking contents, applied teflon tape to the cap and resealed the car. Note:this was one of eight cars that was identified from Mexico shipper that was not properly sealed for transport. Product was neutralized and area was cleared and released to the railroad at 1550.
column169: Oxy Vinyls, KCS railroad have notifed the shipper and are inspecting all cars from the shipper to ensure proper sercurement for transport.

column168: The package flew on FedEx flight 0649/01 from EWR - MEM, transited the Memphis Hub to FedEx Fit 0057/01 from MEM - BQN, transiting Puerto Rico to FedEx fit 8129 from BQN - POS. Once the package was in POS we were in the process of interlining the package to a passenger carrier who x-rayed the package and that's when the six - 175g aerosol can were identified. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information, nor identifying information on the airway bill or commercial invoice to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I left a message foR HazMat Program Manager Janet McLaughlinin Washington DC. We are attempting to obtain digital pictures of the box and contents for the FAA. The freight is being held pending a disposition from the FAA.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: A tanker trailer arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  The trailer was parked in containment on an incline.  It was noticed that the rear hatch was leaking.  A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found that the dome hatch had not been tightened and secured.  Further investigation found that there was spilled material in the driveway entrance to the facility.  No further spillage was found.  The spill was cleaned up with absorbent pads.  The tanker then was accepted by the plant for unloading.   The incident was reported to Illinois Emergency Management Agency, case number H 2011-0222.
column169: The driver was found to not have inspected the dome hatches to insure they were properly secured.  He had been told by someone at the generator that he "was all set".  The driver received a five day disciplinary suspension without pay for failure to perform a proper pre and post trip inspection.

column168: A rolloff vacuum box was being set off at the ten day storage lot of the intended waste disposal facility.  The box was not sliding off of the rails of the truck smoothly and the driver raised the rails all the way up and was jerking the truck to get the box to break free and slide down.  The rear seal of the vacuum box broke loose instead, and some of the liquid contents sprayed down to the ground.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill with a suitable absorbent material.  They also power washed the affected area.  The cleanup material was placed into a suitable salvage container and taken to the intended waste disposal facility along with the vacuum box.
column169: The driver was to be retrained in proper unloading procedures of rolloff containers when he returns to his home terminal.

column168: Five ctns of paint arrived in Spokane Wa on Conway PRO 562814836. They were loaded on the tail of trailer 317-6714. The ctns were not palletized, deck loaded and no other shipments were loaded next to them. Two of the ctns were leaking gray paint.    One ctn containing 2 each 2.5 liter cans of UN1263, paint, 3, PGIII was crushed on the side by unknown object and actions, which resulted in the top of one can being popped open from liquid compression. Estimated approximately 2 ounces of paint was released in the spill.     One ctn containing 6 each 1 quart cans of UN1263, paint, 3, PGII was wet with gray paint leaking from inside. No apparent physical damage to ctn. Inspection revealed one can was leaking past the lid for unknown reason. Estimated less then one ounce of paint released, but ctn was stained and all 6 cans were slightly damaged by paint.     The release was very small, mostly absorbed by the cardboard overpacking materials. All the damaged product was placed in a plastic bag and stored in a 8 gallon recovery drum at Conway Spokane service center. All cleanup was performed by USK FOS James Riley.

column168: On 3/4/2011 at 16:28 hrs., personnel in the CSXT / Carolina Public Railways State Junction Interchange yard, discovered TILX 200244, a loaded tank car of Acetic Acid, Glacial, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, BP Amoco Chemical Company, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-03-04-00202.  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product dripping from the bottom outlet cap. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Greg Crum at 630-420-5018. HEPACO personnel removed the auxiliary valve plug and opened the line to drain the trapped product into a container. HEPACO personnel were unsuccessful at tightening the bottom outlet cap.  Since the trapped product was removed between the main and auxiliary valve, the rail car was temporarily secured. The shipper was informed that an FRA Movement Approval would be required to forward the car to destination due to the defective bottom outlet valve.    On 3/9/2011 at 15:00 hrs., personnel in the CSXT / Carolina Public Railway's State Junction Interchange yard discovered TILX 200244, leaking from the bottom of the car for the second time. The car was isolated and the shipper, BP Amoco Chemical Company, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-03-09-00177. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Greg Crum at 630-420-5018. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and installed a haz hammock under the bottom outlet valve. On 3/16/2011 the shipper contracted emergency response contractors, Eagle/SWS, to transfer the product into tank trucks.    This incident did not require a special switching move.    A 7.1 report will be completed for this incident.    Cause Code: 580  5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = NARRI 100

column168: On March 2nd, 2011, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU 849506-9 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On March 3rd 2011, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: Driver was traveling North from Princeton, KY on KY Highway 91 near the 17 mile marker and rounded a curve at approximately 0815 hours on 03/21/2011.  He was driving a 2007 Mack Granite, tri-axle auger truck carrying two types of blasting agent.  They were UN0331 and UN0332.  The driver stated he was meeting another truck (loaded with rock) that was sightly on the center line in a curve when he moved over as close to the shoulder of the road as he could to avoid a head on collision when his right front tire dropped off the shoulder of the road way.  He attempted to steer back on to the roadway when the vehicle skidded and over turned.  The driver assessed the situation for personal injuries and contacted emergency personnel and then his supervisor.  State Police, EMS, DOT/Vehicle Enforcement, State Fire Marshal, EPA, Ambulance, State Highway Dept as well as local athorities were notified.  Each responder began their investigation and then clean up began.  Spilled product was contained and did not enter into a water way or stream.  Residents in the immediate area were notified and evacuated for precautionary measures.  Carrier notified the NRC Hotline and filed report as per required.
column169: Road way in this area is very narrow.  This driver as well as other drivers will be trained as to watch for other oncoming traffic and narrow roadways.  Training methods will include slowing to a safe speed to meet conditions of particular road ways and possibly turning on hazard warning lights in these areas.  Changes will be made to the doors on top of the containers for added securement.  Defensive driver training will be included in the retraining of the driver involved.

column168: DSR was loading a pallet into the trailer when his forktines ran into the pallet and punctured a box containing 2/1 gallon cans of paint. Driver reported that as soon as he started product flowing from the cargo tank to the consignee storage tank, he noticed product coming from an open valve on our transfer pump.  He had checked everything before he started the unload but overlooked that valve.  He immediately shut down.  He said about 1 gallon went on dirt. Nothing got in any drains.  He secured the valve and completed the unload.  Cleanup was done under direction of customer.
column169: Driver did not follow proper procedure by ensuring all valves were closed.  He is scheduled for remedial training.

column168: At approximately 2300 hrs.our drivers enterd the GE Romolands premises and wemt through thier security protocols. At 2311 hrs began the off load process and about 10 minutes into the off load process when a release of 29.5% of aqaua ammonia was released from a rupture of the jumper hose near the pump area. The rupture was in the middle of the hose. The driver hit the emergency shut off switch immediately, in at the nose of the trailer which is where he was standing at the time of the release. The customer was alerted of the release and they beat down the vapor with a water hose. It was estimated that approximately 50 gallons was spilled. The driver was release by the customer and he left their property at 2350 hrs.
column169: The preventative measures that were put into place is that we converted our entire fleet jumper hose to a stainless steel flex hose which is rated at 500 PSI. This  hose is also checked on the drivers pre-trip but it is now checked on our California BIT inspection which is every 90 days for structural integrity.

column168: A rolloff box containing hazardous waste was brought back to the yard for storage and further transport to the intended waste disposal facility.  During a routine yard check, it was noticed that some material had come out of the top of the box and spilled over the side onto the ground.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material and the absorbents used to clean the pavement.  The clean up material was placed back into the box.  The incident was reported to Ohio EPA, incident number 1103-31-0893.
column169: The spill occurred when the box was unloaded from the rolloff truck.  The driver apparently raised the box too high and the material spilled between the tarp and the top edge of the box.  The driver was retrained in proper rolloff unloading procedures.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED FROM THE FEEDER INTACT. IT WAS THEN PLACED ON THE IRREGULAR SLIDE BEFORE BEING MOVED TO THEIRREGULARS BELT. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED ON THE IRREGULARS BELT ON ITS SIDE WITH THE ORIENTATION ARROWS FACING TO THE SIDE.THE PACKAGE TRAVELED ON THE BELT TO THE IRREGULAR SORT AREA IN THE BLUE SECTION OF THE BUILDING. THE P/T SUPERVISOR OBSERVEDTHE WET BOX, STOPPED THE BELT AND CALLED IN THE SPILL AT 02:15 ON 03/08/2011. A DESIGNATE RESPONDER WAS DISPACHED WITH FULL PPEINCLUDING BOOTS, GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON, SLEEVES, SILVER LINERS TO THE SPILL LOCATION. THE RESPONDER APPROACHED THE PACKAGEWITH DECISION TREE AND PROCEEDED TO EVALUATE THE SPILL. WHEN THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER OBSERVED THE CORROSIVE 8 DIAMONDWAS DISPOSED OF IN DMP DURING THE MIDNIGHT SORT.
column169: THIS OCCURANCE COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY USING CORRECT HAND TO SURFACE METHODS WHEN TRANSFERRING PACKAGES TO THE IRREGULAR BELT. IT IS ALSO RECOMMENDED THAT ORIENTATION ARROWS BE OBSERVED AND PACKAGES PLACED IN THE DIRECTION INDICATED BY THE ARROWS.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Houston, Texas on the Buenos Aires Express Voyage 1105S.    The shipment was declared as:    - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Methanol & Isopropanol), Class 3, PG III, FP 42.2C  - UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, NOS (Quaternary Ammonium Compound), Class 8, PG III, Marine Pollutant  - UN1993, Flamamble Liquid, NOS (Methanol), Class 3, PG II, FP 20C    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Houston, that the freight container in fact contained: UN1230, Methanol, Class 3 (6.1), PG II, FP 11C  instead of the 3rd item (UN1993, Flamamble Liquid, NOS (Methanol), Class 3, PG II, FP 20C).    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the correct hazardous material loaded in the container.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the misdeclared/undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: While at the UPRR yard in Livonia, LA, tank car DBUX 251042 was found to be leaking lading from the top of the tank and down the sides.  The car was isolated onto track 97 without incident.  Inspection by UPRR Manager of Hazardous Materials, T. M. Robinson, revealed that the liquid eduction valve was open slightly, and lading was leaking from between the valve flange and flange for the knock tight fitting. The flange gasket had deteriorated and was no longer effective.  Robinson closed the valve completely and this stopped the leak. Technicians from response contractor, Oil Mop, Inc. replaced the gasket.  The spilled lading had solidified on to the top and sides of the tank car.  This material was cleaned off by the Oil Mop technicians.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While physically screening a shipment of tools and parts, I discovered a first aid kit containing a small cold compress that, according to the packaging, contained ammonium nitrate. I suspected this might be dangerous goods, so I called the Alaska Airlines DG Help Desk, which confirmed my suspicion. I returned the item to the shipper, who was very surprised to learn that it was considered DG, as he had sent it on numerous flights in the past.
column169: I would suggest making more of first aid kits as sources of DG during cargo screener training. Also, and more important, I would attempt to increase awareness among contractors and others who carry first aid kits that cold compresses may contain a dangerous chemical.

column168: On 3/25/2011, a New Century Transport tractor trailer suffered a load shift resulting in the release of UN1917 Ethyl Acrylate inside the trailer. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for remediation activities. The contractor off-loaded the cargo and located the damaged drum. The drum was overpacked and placed back on the trailer for continued transportation. The released material evaporated and no cleanup was necessary.

On March 03, 2010, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU782992-1 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1133 Adhesives). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. column168: Three closure point failures occured with this car:    One - Broken thermometer well tube.    Two - deteriorated O-ring.    Three - missing cap seal.    The thermometer well nipple and cap were removed and replaced with a pipe plug.    the car was discovered with product releasing from the thermometer well tube cap.    Three closure point failures occured with this car.    one-broken thermometer well tube.  this allowed product to get inside the tube.    two-missing cap gasket.  This allowed product to leave the tube.    Three- deteriorated cap O-ring.  This allowed product that escaped past the missing cap gasket to leave the tube.  The car was allowed to go to atmospheric pressure.  The release stopped.  The thermometer well nipple and cap were removed and replaced with a pipe plug to secure the car.

column168: A vacuum box container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended Clean Harbors waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the drive conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door of the vacuum box container. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a Clean Harbors response crew was dispatched to the scene where the response crew added a binder chain which stopped the leak: a containment diaper was secured to the vacuum box as an added measure. The NY DEC was notified  (Officer Andy Frank) to obtain permission to transport the Vacuum box to the Clean Harbors Glenmont NY Facility to transfer the material into a Tanker for contuinued transportation to intended disposal facility. Officer Franks granted Clean Harbors permission to conduct this procedure. The tanker was escorted by the spill team to ensure the container remained secure back to the Glenmont facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors Glenmont NY facility it  was determined the vacuum box was leaking from the a comprimised gasket. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure that a comprehensive inspection of a container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, this specific container was placed out of service and sent back to the container's owner for repairs.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM. PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.

column168: The driver arrived at the customer’s site at 12:17 and positioned his vehicle at the unloading area at a slight decline. He then proceeded to connect a 2" chemical unloading hose to the intermediate bulk container,(IBC) to be offloaded and the unloading pump. (2) 2" chemical hoses were then connected to the outlet of the unloading pump to the customers receiving tank. The employee secured all hose connections with Velcro straps. Upon receiving approval to begin the offloading process the employee activated the offloading pump by engaging the air, and opened the IBC valve. The employee then observed all connections to ensure there were no leaks.  The employee transferred (3) IBCs to the customers receiving tank to complete the delivery. While the employee was disconnecting the chemical hoses an employee of the customer informed the driver that he had HCL leaking on the ground. At this time the driver noticed the last tote he transferred had leaked product which ran behind the valve onto the trailer floor towards the front of the trailer due to the vehicle being parked on a decline. The driver then proceeded to clean up the area affected by the release. The recovered material was containerized for subsequent disposal. The driver returned the transport vehicle to the shipping facility for further examination.  All the hoses used in the transfer process were inspected. (1) hose that was connected to the valve of the IBC was found to have a compromised gasket. The hose was then connected to the tote which had leaked to determine if there was a proper connection. The hose was able to spin freely on the valve connection indicating the gasket had been compromised. The IBC was DOT tested on 3/28/11 to verify the leak had not occurred due to gasket failure in the valve and passed.
column169: To prevent future occurrences all employees who perform bulk unloading processes were instructed to changed hose gaskets when they perform their monthly hose inspections. The employees were also instructed to inspect all hose gaskets prior to any bulk unloading and replace if the visual inspection of the gasket expressed and damage or compromises. This incident was also reviewed during the facility safety meeting.

column168: Container number CXCU8784755 was received in the marine terminal and loaded to the Horizon Tacoma on 3/30/2011.  The customer submitted hazardous paperwork for the 40 cartons of lithium batteries the following morning following the vessel sailing.  The cargo was received, loaded to the vessel and sailled without knowledge from the shipper that the cargo was hazardous.
column169: The shipper acknowledged that they had made an error in communications and forwarded the paperwork to Horizon Lines upon discovery of the problem.  They are going to review their procedures to ensure that this incident does not happen again.

column168: At approximately 10:30A on Wednesday 03/16/2011, Transportation Services Unlimited Inc., hereinafter “TSUI” driver James Ellis called the TSUI Ranger, Georgia dispatch to report an equipment failure (cargo tanker unloading hose, put into service 01/08/2010) resulting in a release of hazardous material, sodium hypochlorite (UN1791) to the delivery site’s, American Development Corporation or “ADC”, parking lot.  The duration of the spill is undetermined as the start time of the hose failure resulting in the spilled material is unknown.  At 10:35A, Ranger, Georgia Branch Manager, Jim Novak, called Mike Gentry with ADC to access the situation and see what further assistance was needed, if any.  At first, Mr. Novak was informed that the spill involved approximately 50 gallons of sodium hypochlorite which had been contained and was being pumped to an intermediate bulk container.  At 12:05P, Mr. Ellis, the driver, called the TSUI Ranger, Georgia dispatch to report unloading operations were continuing as the cargo tanker unloading hose had been repaired.  However, Mr. Ellis noted that per his estimation, 1027 gallons of sodium hypochlorite had been released, not 50 gallons, of which 275 gallons was contained and reclaimed to the intermediate bulk container.  Mr. Novak and Mr. Gentry resumed their conversation, and Mr. Gentry informed Mr. Novak that the spilled sodium hypochlorite had flowed from the parking lot into a drainage area, which had receive heavy rains and stormwater runoff the previous evening,  where the material was pooling.  Using a kit to test the available chlorine (i.e. pool test kit), Mr. Gentry determined the pooled material in the drainage area was less than 3% available sodium hypochlorite.  Based upon this conversation and discussion with senior company management, TSUI contacted its insurance carrier, Chartis, to dispatch a hazardous material/environmental clean-up crew to evaluate the scene and address remediation concerns.  ADC, under the instruction of the local Emergency Management Agency/Fire Response, instructed ADC to neutralize the spilled material by applying a non-hazardous material (calcium thiosulfate).  Once neutralization was completed, it was determined by the Emergency Management Agency/Fire Response, no further action was needed.  At 6:30P, Eagle SWS, environmental contractor contacted by Chartis, arrived at the scene and conducted their own assessment, including pH testing and briefing from ADC regarding actions taken to mitigate/neutralize the spill (including the instructions of the Emergency Management Agency/Fire Response).  At 7:13P, all parties agreed that the necessary actions had been taken to mitigate the spill of sodium hypochlorite with further pH monitoring of the area over the next several days.  When cargo tanker returned to the TSUI Ranger, Georgia facility, it was determined through weight/trip reports that 1095 gallons of 12.5% by weight sodium hypochlorite (UN1791) had been lost from the cargo ta

column168: Driver of Transport used a 3 x 2 poly connector to string (2) hoses together instead of using a stainless connector.  When he started pumping off product the poly connector started to leak because of the amount of heat passing through it at the time.  Poly plastics and heat don't mix!
column169: At no time are drivers to utilize poly connectors unless authorized by the Safety Department.  This particular driver has been reprimended for his inattention to details.

column168: Employee heard some hissing and thought he blew tire or airbag on the suspension but his air pressure did not drop.  Employee looked back in his mirror and he could see the shadow of a cloud of propane in the air.    Employee pulled over into abandoned restaurant and called a mechanic shop 5 miles away.  The mechanic brought over a trailer that was being repaired. Employee off loaded all the propane from his trailer into the trailer the mechanic brought.    The release was coming from the pressure relief valve.  It is a Fisher Valve.  The stem on the valve broke off.  Ferrellgas has had problems with this valve in the past.    An IL State trooper stopped and left shortly after saying that it looks like Employee had everything under control.
column169: The defective valve issue is being addressed with the manufacturer.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On 03/19/2011 at 15:35 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Montgomery, AL rail yard discovered UTLX 201987, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., leaking liquid from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, ExxonMobil Chemical Co., was notified thru CHEMTREC Report 2011-03-19-00077. USES Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the liquid valve where it is attached to the liquid line pipe was leaking, this allowed product to spill on to the rail car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ernesto Johnson 225-977-8133.   USES Environmental took the valve off the pipe, cleaned the pipe and reattached it to the pipe with a pipe wrench. The leak was secured and the car was held for an FRA movement approval to be requested by the shipper since car did not comply with government regulations.     This incident did require a special switch move.   No 7.1 will be required for this incident    Cause Code: 282  NARRI: 40

The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Norfalco Sales Inc., was notified thru Canadian Emergency contact 1-613-996-6666 no report number was given. column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc received a call from the enviornmental & compliance department of the City of Jacksonville stating we had a spill at a customer location. After investigation of this incident it was determined to not be known exactly what procedure was done incorrectly to cause the incident as the driver continually denied that it had occured. Most likely the Florida Rock driver had not properly hooked up the coupling to the hose and therefore causing the approximately 10 gallons to leak onto the concrete and running to the nearby soil. We have removed the asphalt and soil that was affected by the spill. Clean soil and asphalt have been place at the site. Had the incident been reported when it occured by the driver, product would have been cleaned immediately and possibly not entered onto soil.
column169: The driver was terminated from his employment for failing to report the spill in a timely manner, as based on amount of product and location of spill, the product would not have reached soil had the spill been properly handled.

column168: While unloading IBC from trailer material handler discover a very small puddle underneath the bottom outlet. No action contributed to this failure and it was determined that the unintentional release was coming from the outlet threads. Repair putty was placed onto the threads which fixed the problem and the IBC was returned to the shipper as per instructed. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent.
column169: Perhaps consider putting internal valves in future construction of IBC's so if there is a problem with the bottom outlet there is a fail safe. Right now when there is a problem with a bottom outlet there is no way to stop the flow of product and an internal valve might help contain and control in such situations.

column168: A driver was loading a tanker with hazardous waste liquid at a customer's site in a containment area.  The load gauge showed less than full when there was a gurgling sound heard.  The product had begun foaming and leaking out of the scrubber.  The unit was shut down immediately.  The driver was wearing the appropriate personal protective equipment at the time along with the customer's supervisor.  The material was immediately cleaned up.  The foaming ceased, the level of the tanker was visibly checked through the dome and found to still have over 12 inches of free space remaining.  The loading process then continued without further incident.
column169: The product was being transferred from a frac tank into the tanker trailer.  The foaming of the product was not anticipated and caused the tanker and valves to be overfilled.  Once the waste quit foaming, it continued to be loaded without incident.  Further care will be taken on further loads of this material.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During the driver's post trip inspection, he noticed a small amount of liquid dripping from the floor of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and entered the trailer.  A flex bin was found to be leaking, totally soaked through by the contents.  The bin was repacked into a suitable salvage container and the trailer floor and ground underneath was cleaned and the clean up material also placed into the salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The generator was notified as to the high liquid content of the material which was described as a solid.  They advised they would review their processes to see why the material failed to be properly dried.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility. Tennessee Emergency Management Authority was notified and assigned Case number 502.  The shipment continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The generator was notified of the incident and advised to use caution when using old corroded drums.  The driver was also cautioned to use better care in inspecting and accepting old used drums.

column168: A Clean Harbors tractor and trailer were parked inside secondary containment at loading dock.  Offeror (Merck) experienced fork truck driver was loading pallets onto shipper's van trailer.  Each pallet had 4 x 55 gallon drums of Ethanol being shipped for recycle.  After loading approximately 6 pallets, fork truck driver set next pallet inside trailer.  Fork truck driver backed up and then decided to move pallet slightly over closer to wall of the trailer.  The forks were not level as the fork truck driver went in to get another grab of the pallet.  One of the forks punctured the side of a 55 gallon steel drum approximately 1 inch from the bottom of the drum.  Fork truck driver immediately removed fork truck, put down absorbant pads and spill booms inside trailer.  Fork truck driver contacted supervisor and shipper project manager.  Liquids not absorbed by pads and booms was captured in secondary containment and later pumped into a drum for future shipment.

Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering ultra low sulfer diesel to a customer location. While unloading the driver noticed the pressure began to build up in the tank. According to both the stick readings and the veeder root reading the load of 1000 gallons should have easily fit. The driver stopped the flow of product and attempted to release some of the pressure by disconnecting the stomp down. Before he was able to replace the cap, the driver noticed prodcut leaking from the ground tank. Approximatley 15 gallons was released onto the asphalt. No product reached soil or drains. The Fire Department, Florida Rock Regional Manager and SWS First Response responded to the scene. The product was all contained and cleaned to everyone's satisfaction.
column169: The station where the driver was delivering had a malfuction with their tanks and had the driver not unhooked the stomp down the responsibility would have been solely on the station to repair their tanks. However rather than just stop the flow and report the problem or make sure the hose is completely clear before removing the stomp down, the driver ended up causing the spill. The driver will be required to attend unloading training and incident prevention observations will be conducted on the driver. The station has also since repaired their tank issue.

column168: A petroleum product odor was reported within the classification tracks of the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified and searched the area for the odor source. Tank car TILX 190949 was found with a drying product stain on its side shell. A detailed inspection of TILX 190949 revealed that the one inch vapor valve was in the full open position and its closure plug was not applied. The responders closed the vapor valve, applied and tool tightened the closure plug ending the product odor and further release. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The valve housing cover was sealed with BNSF seal numbered 06157793. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was observed. Response was concluded by 1010 hrs. PST, 3/10/2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car TILX 210041 entrained in an outbound BNSF train in the railyard was reported leaking product from the top fitting area of the B-end compartment of this three compartment tank car. TILX 210041 was carefully set-out of the train for detailed inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders. The responders reported finding the B-end liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not tool tight which allowed product to escape from plug closure area. The responders closed the valve and tool tightened the closure plug which ended further product release. All other valves and fittings appeared secure. Spillage on the tank shell rapidly evaporated and no ground impact was observed. Intact shipper seal numbered 012154 was replaced by BNSF seal numbered 06157646.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: A FRA hazardous material inspection in the railyard revealed tank car HOKX 112323 with product residue on its side shell. HOKX 112323 was visually inspected by BNSF mechanical personnel and carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting furtherance. Contract responders were called to neutralize and clean spillage off this tank car; and determine the root cause of product release. The responders reported that the leak source was at the flange base of the 75 psig Midland pressure relief device (PRD). This PRD had a flat faced mounting surface and the mounting gasket was not sealing due to deterioration (cracked with surface separation). The responders replaced this gasket and resecured the PRD upon the mounting flange. Spillage on the side shell was neutralized and cleaned.   HOKX 112323's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification and PRD retest/inspection were completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

During a BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard, tank car DOWX 3900 was reported emanating a product odor. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected DOWX 3900, finding the odor source at the manway closure. Responders reported six manway securement bolts were less than tool tight which prevented a good closure seal. The responders properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts (3 bolts at 1/2 turn and 3 bolts at 1/4 turn to achieve a tool tight condition). Afterwards, product odor/vapor dissipated. The manway gasket was not inspected and the intact shipper seal at the manway was not disturbed. No liquid product release was observed. Response was concluded by 1245 hrs. PDT, 3/19/2011.

column168: Tank car GATX 6332 in the railyard was reported leaking product from the top fitting area. GATX 6332 was cordoned off in the railyard with plastic receptacles placed under GATX 6332 to capture liquid dripping off its side shell.  BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders found the liquid line closure plug less than hand tight.  Responders tool tightened this closure plug which ended further product release by 1711 hrs. CDT, 3/23/2011. Responders also found the air/vapor line closure plug was hand tight and it was tool tightened. Seal BNSF 002446 was applied, as no shipper seals were present. The fill hole cover was opened to check the product outage level and the outage level was deemed appropriate. The cover was resecured and intact seal numbered 5231609 was replaced by seal BNSF 002447. Spillage on the top tank and side shell was neutralized with water/baking soda solution. Product spillage on the ground was observed and the ground impact area was then surrounded by caution tape. On 3/24/2011, remediation contractor applied soda ash to neutralize ground spillage. Impacted ballast and top soils were excavated and placed into disposal drums for appropriate future disposal.   The local F.D. initiated a precautionary evacuation that impacted nearby small businesses and two households for approximately 1 1/2 hours.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: KCS' reporting GATX 201416, located in track 7 Port Arthur yard, load Ammonia Anhydrous, 2.2, UN1005 from Martin Products sales Beaumont (their contact Shane Nerriman 409-673-1380) was found with a slight ammonia odor emission from a defective reclosable pressure relief device. The offeror initially mobilized Rescar for repair, but they did not have the correct o-ring size. KCS mobilized USES with correct o-ring for repair.    KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.    Item 19: No liquid product was released by this car. Only product odor vapors were release. PHMSA DOT reporting system defects will not allow reporting release in units other than what is used for reporting capcity. Therefore this vapor odor release was reported as 0.1 gallon to make the PHMSA DOT system accept report.    Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was required to facilitate data acceptance by defective PHMSA DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required for two reasons:   (1)because the shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and   (2)because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field which match the same units of measure as found in the capacity field.   KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On March 9, 2011 a Linden Bulk Trailer was receiving a load of Ketrul D75 (naptha) at IMTT-Bayonne.  Towards the end of the transfer the Linden driver, who was on top of the trailer compartment getting a manual gauge of the product, reported to the IMTT Operator that the contents of the trailer had overflowed.  The IMTT Operator immediately shut down the operation.  IMTT personnel used absorbant pads to wipe down the outside of the trailer compartment and placed pads on the impacted areas of the loading rack.  Arrangments were made to pump back the excess product from the trailer compartment to the appropriate storage tank.  Once the product level in the trailer was at safe fill, the trailer was released.
column169: After a thorough investigation IMTT determined that the overfill was caused by a combination of human error on the part of the IMTT Operator and a malfunction of the electronic meter on the loading rack.  The IMTT Operator has been counseled by his supervisor and re-trained.  The meter has been repaired and is back in service.

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported a strong product odor emanating from intermodal containers (destined for export) riding upon an intermodal flatcar that was previously setout from an inbound BNSF train per schedule. An on site BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was immediately notified.  The responder reported that a 20 ft. IM-101 intermodal tank container BLKU 125296 (AAR U621 car kind) was the odor source. Detailed inspection of BLKU 125296 revealed that its manway closure bolts were not tool tight but finger loose. These manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened by the responder. A small amount of liquid product retained in the fabricated containment pan around the manway closure was absorbed by absorbent material, removed and the area wiped. Afterwards, all product odors dissipated. No ground impact from this product release was observed.

column168: Please note that Schenker, Inc. shall be named as the reporting party only. According to the information obtained, the following occurred. The area was isolated, and Schenker Dangerous Goods Specialists Sedina Spahija and Eduardo Perez responded to perform the cleanup. Dangerous Goods Specialists Spahija and Perez performed an investigation and determined that one (1), 50-gallon steel drum had been that there was a scratch on the bottom of the drum causing leaking. Absorbent materials (sand) were placed on the spilled product on the floor. Dangerous Goods Specialists Spahija and Perez, with assistance from terminal dock personnel, placed the damaged, 50-gallon steel drum into a salvage/recovery drum along with the cleanup materials. The salvage drum and all its contents have been shipped to the consignee.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product odor emanating from tank car CPCX 102013 in the railyard. CPCX 102013 was cordoned off and all workers in the railyard were kept upwind from CPCX 102013's location. A BNSF hazardous material responder inspected CPCX 102013 finding the odor/vapor source at the vapor valve area.  The vapor valve was found slightly open and its operating handle was re-positioned to fully close the vapor valve. Also, one of the four vapor valve's blind or closure flange bolts was not tool tight. The responder removed the blind flange and replaced the flange gasket to ensure a good seal and resecured the blind flange. Afterwards, all residue product odor/vapor dissipated by 0230 hrs. hrs. CDT, 3/31/2011. Intact shipper seal ALB 188881 was replaced by seal BNSF Hazmat 1949.

column168: At 12:30P EST, TSUI driver notified his supervisor of spilled sodium hypochlorite at a customer location, Gorman 1006 SE 9th Lane, Cape Coral, FL 33990.  Driver stated the unloading hose failed, developed a leak in the hose leading to the spraying of sodium hypochlorite in the immediate area.  Driver immediately discontinued the unloading of sodium hypochlorite from cargo tanker upon discovery of the leak.  It was determined about fifteen (15) gallons of sodium hypochlorite product was released from the hose failure point to the ground and onto a parked vehicle.  Vehicle was rinsed with water by the TSUI driver.  The owner of the property called the Fire Department.  The Fire Department responded to the scene, placing absorbent material in front of the storm/sewer drains.  They also assisted with removing the remaining sodium hypochlorite material in the unloading hose and flushing the area with water.  The Fire Department notified the Florida State Warning Point (report number SWP110325-1660), but incorrectly identified the material as liquid chlorine.  A Florida Department of Environmental Protection (FDEP) officer was dispatched to the scene (# BER 2011-3I-44975).  It was determined that an environmental contractor, Cliff Berry, would handle all remaining remediation required by the FDEP.  Water and sodium hypochlorite came into contact with oil marks/stains on the surface prior to flowing to the soil.  FDEP officer noted due to the mixture of oil, additional clean-up actions were required.
column169: The delivery site may have caused the hose failure.  The hose has to be “dragged” under a chain link fence in order to connect to the above ground storage tank for unloading.  Dragging across surface and chain link fence may have damaged hose causing failure.  Hence, working with customer to redesign delivery or discontinue delivery to this site.

column168: Intermodal tank container SNTU 700549 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of container.  Container isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found product vapor escaping from the manway.  Tightening the manway bolts temporarily stopped the vapor release.  The following day at 07:00 hrs product odor was again detected and the contractor returned and found the manway cover gasket was defective allowing vapor to escape.  The manway cover gasket was replaced and the manway lid properly secured stopping the release.      The NRC was notified of the second release and is covered by NRC Report number 971747.

SINCE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BOX ITSELF THE RESPONDER BROUGHT THE BOX BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA FOR FUTHER INVESTIGATION. FUTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE PAINT THINNER CAN HAD A LOOSE CAP AND WAS TOUCHING THE CARTON WALL.
column169: RECOMMEND THAT PADDING (PAPER, SPRAY FOAM, BUBBLE WRAP, ETC) BE PLACED ON ALL FOUR SIDES OF THE CONTENT INSIDE THE BOX. I ALSO RECOMMEND THAT ALL CAPS BE CHECKED AND SECURED WITH STRONG TAPE THAT INHIBITS THE CAP FROM MOVING PRIOR TO THE BOX BEING SEALED FOR TRANSPORT.  I ALSO RECOMMEND THAT UPS REMINDS ALL EMPLOYEES TO PROPERLY BRACE HAZMAT PACKAGES ON ALL FOUR SIDES AND ENSURE ORIENTATION ARROWS ARE ALWAYS FACING THE APPROPRIATE DIRECTION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: AN EMPLOYEE PROCESSING A LARGE PACKAGE AT THE UPS CHICAGO AREA CONSOLIDATION HUB NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE APPEARED TO BE SMOKING. AFTER THE MANAGEMENT TEAM WAS APPROPRIATELY NOTIFIED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE FIRE CHIEF DETERMINED THAT BECAUSE THE BOX EXHIBITED TO MARKINGS, THE BOMB SQUAD SHOULD BE CALLED.  BY THE TIME THE BOMB SQUAD ARRIVED, THE PACKAGE WAS NO LONGER SMOKING.  LOCAL FBI AGENTS ALSO ARRIVED.  EFFORTS TO X-RAY THE PACKAGE YIELDED NO USEFUL INFORMATION, SO THE AUTHORITES DETERMINED TO "SHOOT" THE PACKAGE IN AN EFFORT TO TRIGGER A REMOTE DETONATION.  AFTERWARDS, THE CONTENTS WERE FOUND TO BE A LARGE TRUCK BATTERY.  THE BATTERY WAS CRACKED ON THE SIDE AND MAY HAVE DAMAGED THROUGH PACKAGE HANDLING (OR SYSTEM RELATED), DAMAGED PRIOR TO SHIPPING, OR DAMAGED WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS SHOT WITH THE HIGH PRESSURE WATER PARTICILES.  HOWEVER, THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT CANNOT BE DETERMINED FROM THE REMAINS.
column169: THE LACK OF APPROPRIATE LABELS OR MARKINGS TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS AS A BATTERY CREATED UNCERTAINTY FOR UPS AND OUTSIDE RESPONDERS.  WHILE THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE ARE CLEARLY A LEAD-ACID BATTERY, IT IS UNKNOWN IF THE BATTERY MAY HAVE BEEN QUALIFIED TO COMPLY WITH THE CONDITIONS APPLICABLE TO BATTERY, WET, NON-SPILLABLE (UN2800). SHIPPER COMPLIANCE WITH THE HAZARD COMMUNICATION REQUIREMENTS WOULD HAVE HELPED REDUCE THE UNCERTAINTY ABOUT THE SHIPMENT CONTENTS.

column168: LOADER TIPPED PALLET OVER WHEN LOADING AND PUNCTURED FREIGHT WITH FORKS.  THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS! RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING THE VARIOUS PACKAGES.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLCOKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.

The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

column168: DUPX 29205 was called in as having a bad smell by job 236 at 17:55, I found the car in track 10 and inspected the car, all dome lid bolts appeared to be tight, however there was a strong odor coming from the dome lid area. I had the crew stay upwind of the car by the covered shed on the south end of Pasadena. I then set it over to track 15 to have ICT come and place a new seal in the dome lid.    Mr. Richard Hardgrove with ICT called at 18:04 stating that he was in rout to the plant to get some tools as well as new gaskets and he would meet me at Pasadena to fix the issue. Mr. Hardgrove arrived at 18:45 and the car was repaired with a new gasket at 19:
column169: ITC started a new procedure Monday, once a MA car is finished loading,  man way secured we will put 15 to 20 psi of pressure on car, snoop man  way checking for leaks.  If leak is found we will tight man way to see  if leak stops, if not we will relieve pressure open man way and replace  gasket.  Repeat the pressure test, if pressure test holds we will leave  pressure on car over night, check car first thing in the morning if no  leaks are found we will put car on the pull track for shipment.  We will  be using dry air for the pressure test NO Nitrogen will be used.

column168: At 0245 EST, TSUI driver was unloading sodium hypochlorite at a customer location, Sunbelt Chemicals, 71 Hargrove Grade, Palm Coast, Fla.  Driver stated that a stationary hose is left at this customer to unload the tankers as they come for night deliveries.  Driver states that he had been unloading the sodium hypochlorite for approximately 10 – 15 minutes when he noticed a puddle of liquid around a section of the hose.  With his personal protection equipment on he approached this area to investigate what this liquid was and why it was there and detected a bleach smell.  He at once shut down his unloading process and blew out the product left in the line into the customer’s tank.  He noticed that there was a pin hole in the hose which was causing it to slowly leak sodium hypochlorite on the ground.  At 0315, following our safety procedures the driver called Allied Universal Corp. Branch Manager, Randy Bunkley notifying him of this leak and that he was going to use the hose off his tanker to complete that unloading process.  At this time the small amount of sodium hypochlorite, which had leaked out, had already soaked into the ground.  The driver could not wash down the area because the customer did not have water available at this site.  The main water is shut off nightly.
column169: THE STATIONARY HOSE THAT WAS AT THE CUSTOMER SITE WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE BRANCH AND REPLACED WITH A NEW HOSE

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported tank car UTLX 210539 leaking product from a top fitting area during movement in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 210539 finding the product leak emanating from the McKenzie high-flow 165 psi safety relief valve (SRV). UTLX 210539 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Spillage on the UTLX 210539's side shell evaporated and no additional product loss was observed when UTLX 210539 remained motionless. No ground impact from spillage was reported. A failed SRV was suspected and a replacement SRV was ordered. The replacement SRV was received and installed on 4/08/2011 without further incident. The failed SRV was missing its spring and the bottom spring hardware (spring retainer, the stem hex nut and the stem lock nut) which is indicative of a broken bottom valve stem.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 3-21-2011 the CLI TRansport, LP driver selected a trailer in the yard that was placed out of service by the shop, however a red tag was not placed on the trailer. The driver did not see the gap in the piping during his pretrip inspection. The spill occurred at the loading rack while the driver was attempting to load product.  Driver heard the leak and stopped the loading process immediately. All 30 gallons were recovered by the loading rack in there oil seperator. The trailer should have been placed out of service with a red tag; communicating to the driver there was an issue.  The terminal manager had a discussion with the shop to always use red tags when trailers are placed out of service and to let termial manager know as a backup to avoid errors in the future.
column169: Red tags will be utilized by the shop on all equipment placed out of service.

Employee backed up to the riser, left the truck running, did not use chock blocks, and did not take keys out of ignition or key loop.  Employee loaded his truck and did not do the walk around. column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While travelling on Oklahoma Highway 3, near Sara Road, the tractor-tanker unit was involved in a vehicle accident.  Apparently the accident resulted as a result of a vehicle pulling out in front of the tractor-tanker unit.  The tractor-tanker unit hit the vehicle on the passenger side of the car and the unit rolled over and into a ditch on the side of the road.  The unit was hauling approximately 6500 gallons of unleaded gasoline and 1500 gallons of diesel fuel.  As a result of the accident, and rollover the unit caught on fire.  The Oklahoma City Fire Department and the Oklahoma City Police Department responded to assess the site.  The Oklahoma City Fire Department extinguished the fire and constructed a berm to contain the water and fuel.  Sisk Environmental of Yukon, Oklahoma was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Sisk Environmental performed a site investigation and confirmed that no product had reached any surface waters.  Sisk Environmental recovered the free product on the impacted roadway and completed site excavation as needed.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and was the result of a vehicle accident, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: When one of the pumps was removed for service, the product line was plugged to prevent any excess product from leaking when not connected to a pump. The line had been plugged for a few days when the gasket/seal from the plug began to leak. Less than 3 gallons of product that were in the line were spilled into the containment tank. During a visual inspection of the line/components, it was noticed that the gasket/seal from the plug was not making proper contact and leaked product. The product was removed by a third party contractor and the cap was replaced with a proper gasket.
column169: Moving forward, when a pump is removed for service, the line will be plugged as required and a visual inspection of that plug will be conducted on a daily basis to ensure it is in proper working order.

column168: The crew of the Livorno Express discovered the leaking container on 25 March 2011. The Master, K. W. Nerurkar reported the leak to the shipping line Hapag Lloyd. Hapag Lloyd reported the incident to the USCG, Georgia Port Authority (GPA) and CBP and requested that the USCG attend the vessel, on arrival in Savannah. National Cargo Bureau (49 CFR 176.18) representing Hapag Lloyd and Eagle-SWS (An environmental services company) were also requested to attend the vessel on arrival. The vessel arrived in Savannah, GA, on 4 April 2011 at 21:00 hours.The Chief Officer of the vessel, C. S. Aranjo reported the following: "Deck crew were involved in checking lashings. During the Operation the leaking liquid was seen coming out of the container which had IMDG placards. Immediately they informed the Chief Officer, on the bridge. Work in the area was stopped , container contents checked from the IMDG manifest and EMS was checked. The area was then cordoned off using sand and reports were sent." The USCG boarded the vessel and determined that the container should be discharged and isolated, so that it's contents could be examined. At 00:10 on 5 April the container was discharged from the vessel and isolated in a area near row 608 in Garden City Terminal. The USCG, a representative from the GPA, a GPA Police officer, NCB, and Eagle SWS were present at the containers opening. The following conditions were noted by B. Parrish of NCB : "A pallet ofdrums shifted in the container due to improper securing. The drums inverted and leaked around the lids, but were not punctured. The contents of the container were removed by SWS, and all spilled cargo was cleaned and removed.The drums were returned to the container and properly secured. The USCG observed and approved the operation,and the container was accepted by the vessel based on their approval. P.O.C. for the USCG was PO2 Mudrock (912) 210-2249." At 03:00 hours the container was returned to it's original position on the vessel.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, the TCI Leasing vehicle was involved in an accident, which damaged the freight inside the trailer.  California Highway Patrol responded to the site.  Originally, it was reported to have involved a minimal release of non-regulated floor cleaner.  Patriot Environmental Services of Etiwanda, California was dispatched to offload trailer, containerize leaker, and send load on its way.  However, upon inspection of trailer, it was determined that various commodities had been damaged, and multiple products had released.  Majority of products were shipped as miscellaneous hardware, non-regulated, and/or consumer commodity.  Upon arrival on site, a minimal amount of product was discovered on the asphalt roadway, majority of damaged freight and spilled product were contained inside the trailer.  During offload of freight, it was determined that approximately 8 gallons of muriatic acid, 10 gallons of water-based paint related material, and 4 gallons of roofing tar were released.  Damaged unrecoverable freight consisted of eight (8) 1-gallon plastic pails of muriatic acid, 20-25 pails of water based paint ranging from 1-pint to 1-gallon, and two (2) 5-gallon metal pails of roofing tar.  All damaged product was containerized, trailer and asphalt roadway were cleaned, and remaining freight was repalletized.  Seven (7) 55-gallon drums of waste were transported off site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  TCI Leasing will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: ACTION RESOURCES,INC DRIVER, UNIT 920, TRAILER 4140, DEPARTED CHEROKEE NITROGEN CO. WITH A CARGO OF CONCENTRATED AMMONIUM NITRATE LIQUID AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45, TURNING LEFT ONTO CROSS LANE FOLLOWING THE PRESCRIBED ROUTE. SHORTLY BEFORE 11:00, THE DRIVER CAUGHT SIGHT OF AN UNSECURED RAIN-DRAIN (HOSE) FLAPPING IN HIS RIGHT REAR-VIEW MIRROR. FOCUSING ON THE RIGHT REAR-VIEW MIRROR, THE DRIVER INADVERTENTLY ALLOWED THE RIGHT SIDE TIRES TO LEAVE THE PAVED PORTION OF THE ROAD AND COME UPON A SOFT AND NEARLY NON-EXISTENT SHOULDER. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT HIS STEERING. AS THE VEHICLE BEGAN TO SINK INTO THE SHOULDER, THE LOAD SHIFTED. INERTIAL MOMENTUM OF THE LOAD OVERCAME CENTER OF MASS CAUSING A ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT.    AFTER THE ACCIDENT, THE DRIVER FREED HIMSELF FROM THE VEHICLE AND DISCOVERED CARGO ESCAPING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE LOCATED IN THE DOME-LID OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911, NOTIFIED LOACAL AUTHORITIES, AND THEN CALLED CORPORATE EHS. THE LOCAL TIME WAS - 11:00. FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED AFTER ABOUT TEN MINUTES.    CORPORATE EHS DISPATCHED A VACUUM TANK TRAILER AND TWO MECHANIC/TECHNICIANS TO THE SCENE AT - 11:15. THEY ARRIVED SHORTLY BEFORE 14:00 (114 MILES). THE SUMP VALVE WAS REMOVED FROM THE OVERTURNED TAILER AND THE CARGO TRANFERRED TO THE VACUUM TANKER WITHIN - 40-45 MINUTES. THE RECOVERED CARGO WAS RETURNED TO CHEROKEE NITROGEN, ABOUT A MILE AWAY. ACCORDING TO PLANT SCALES, - 16,000 LBS OF CARGO (1,3000 GALLONS) WAS NOT RECOVERED. VISUAL ESTIMATES SUGGEST THAT THIS NUMBER IS UNUSALLY HIGH, HOWEVER THERE ARE NO OTHER QUANTITATIVE MEASUREMENTS AVAILABLE.    EAGLE-SWS, THE EMERGENCY CLEAN-UP CREW ARRIVED AT 17:00 AND BEGAN CLEANING UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED AT 21:00. THE RECOVERED PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE DELIVERED TO ACTION RESOURCES, INC. IN A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AT - 21:00. IT WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT AN APPROPRIATE LANDFILL FACILITY. THE DAMAGED TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE DELIVERED BY WRECKER SOMETIME PRIOR TO THAT.    IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE CORPORATE EHS MANAGER ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT CHEMTREC THREE TIMES WHILE EN ROUTE TO THE ACCIDENT AT 12:45, 12:50, AND 13:18. ON ALL THREE OCCASIONS A RECORDED MESSAGE SAID "ALL AGENTS ARE BUSY, PLEASE HOLD FOR THE NEXT AVAILABLE AGENT" AFTER WHICH RECORDED MUSIC BEGAN PLAYING. DUE TO INCOMING TELEPHONE TRAFFIC AND NEAR VEHICULAR TRAFFIC, CONTACT WITH AN "AGENT" WAS NOT ESTABLISHED.
column169: EVALUATION OF DRIVER FITNESS AND, IF APPLICABLE, EXTENSIVE RETRAINING. ENVIRONMENTALLY CORRECT DISPOSAL OF SPILL RESIDUES. DISPOSAL OF DAMAGED EQUIPMENT. REVIEW OF INCIDENT AT ALL TERMINALS DURING 2ND QUARTER SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: THE PRODUCT "FLUX" HAD A HIGH API TEMP OF AROUND 300 DEGREES AND WILL REACT TO ANY MOISTURE INSIDE THE TANK. WE TAKE PRECAUTIONS TO ENSURE THE TANK IS DRY PRIOR TO LOADING. WE ALSO PERFORM A VISUAL CHECK TO ENSURE THE TANK IS DRY. IT IS POSSIBLE HOWEVER TO HAVE POCKETS OF MOISUTRE THAT SETS UP IN SMALL AREAS OF THE TANK THAT CANNOT BE SEEN OR WAS NOT FLUSHED COMPLETELY IN THE DRYING PROCESS.    WE ARE AWARE OF THIS. AS A PRECAUTION WE WILL LOAD HOT PRODUCT SLOWLY AND MONITOR THE LOADING FOR ANY SIGNS OF A REACTION. WHEN THIS PRODUCT REACTS TO ANY MOISTURE IT WILL START TO CRACK AND POP, AND THE PRODUCT WILL EXPAND, THIS IS THE REASON WE LOAD THE PRODUCT SLOWLY. ANY REACTION DETECTED AND THE LOADING PROCESS WILL STOP IMMEDIATELY.    WITH THIS LAOD, WE HAD NO REACTIONS AND THE PRODUCT LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE LOADING WAS COMPLETED, WEIGHTS WERE OBTAINED AND THE UNIT WAS IN ROUTE FOR DELIVERY. OUR DRIVER WAS A BLOCK AWAY FROM HIS DELIVERY PINT WHEN NOTICES PRODUCT FOAMING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO TRANSPORT HIS LOAD TO OUR CUSTOMER SITE WHERE THE PRODUCT CONTINUED TO FOAM OVER. OUR HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND THE SITE WAS CLEADNED AND CLEARED.    BASED ON THE OUTCOME OF THE INCIDENT WE CAL ONLY ASSUME THAT SOME MOISTURE REMAINED IN THE TANK BUT DID NOT REACT AT TIME OF LOADING.

column168: THE ACCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON HIGHWAY 2625 APPROXIMATELY 3 MILES WEST OF HWY 31 NEAR MARSHALL, TEXAS. A WEATHERFORD CHEMICAL FLOAT TRUCK WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN ONTO HWY 2625 FROM A LEASE ROAD. THE LEASE ROAD CONTAINED A DOWNWARD GRADE AND AS THE DRIVER ENTERED THE LEFT HAND TURN ONTO HWY 2625, THE CHEMICALS ON THE TRUCK SHIFTED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK CAUSING IT TO ROLL OVER. EMPLOYEES GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK SAFELY AND CALLED THEIR SUPERVISORS TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE ACCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF CHEMICAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE HIGHWAY AND ROADSIDE DITCH FROM THE VARIOUS TOTES THAT HAD RUPTURED DURING THE ACCIDENT. THE TX HIGHWAY PATROL CALLED OUT A HAZMAT CREW TO CONTAIN AND COLLECT RESIDUAL CHEMICALS. ONCE CHEMICALS WERE CONTAINED, WEATHERFORD CONTACTED A CONTRACTOR TO EXCAVATE THE IMPACTED SOILS ALONG HIGHWAY 2625.
column169: REVIEW CURRENT CONVOY POLICY AND MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENT, DISTRICT CONVOY SPEED LIMIT POLICY ON MAJOR HIGHWAYS SET AT 55MPH AND ON RURAL NON-SHOULDERED ROAD SET AT 45 MPH. NEW POLICY WRITTEN AND HAS BEEN REVIEWED WITH ALL PERSONNEL. NEW SPEED LIMIT INFORMATION TO BE POSTED IN ALL VEHICLES. IN ADDITION, WE WILL DEVELOP PROCEDURES TO ENSURE CHEMICALS LOADED ON TRUCK ARE BALANCED. TRAIN ALL EMPLOYEES IN THE NEW PROCEDURE AFTER APPROVAL OF THE PROCEDURE.    THE COMPANY HAS LEASED AND WILL BE INSTALLING VEHICLE MONITORING SYSTEMS IN ALL COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLES THAT WILL PROVIDE DRIVER BEHAVIOR MENTORING AND COACHING, BUT WILL ALLOW ZONES TO BE CREATED FOR DIFFERENT AREAS AND ROAD TYPES. THIS WILL PROVIDE THE DRIVER'S ADDITIONAL WARNING OF POTENTIAL HAZARDOUS AREAS.

column168: A vacuum trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched to Consolidated Edison’s PCB Storage facility in Astoria New York to load PCB contaminated oil for shipment to a properly licensed waste management facility. During the course of loading his trailer, the driver moved the vehicle from the loading site to an on site scale in order to determine available capacity within the tank.  Prior to moving the vehicle, the driver failed to adequately secure the dome hatch on the vehicle which allowed approximately 30 – 50 gallons of material to escape onto the roadway within the confines of the Consolidated Edison property.  Upon realization of the release, representatives from Consolidated Edison initiated both internal and external notifications.  The driver also contacted his home dispatcher and a response crew was assembled and sent to the scene.  Upon arrival, the decision was made to transfer the contents of the trailer to an alternative vehicle to facilitate the disposal of the material and the decontamination of the trailer involved in the spill.  This transfer was accomplished without incident.  Response crews then proceeded to remediate the affected area  that included the deployment of a suitable absorbent, recovery of all spill debris and decontamination and cleaning of all affected surfaces.  All material collected in response to this event was containerized and sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the cause of this release was direclty related to the failure of the driver to secure the cloisures on his vacuum trailer.  As a result of his failure to conduct this basic driver duty, the driver was terminated for cause.  In addition, the local service center prepared an internal incident alert highlighting the factors that led to the release and was reviewed with the operating team involved in this operation.

column168: The roll-off box, RO303, was picked up from the customer, Electro-Coatings of Iowa on March 15, 2011 by HeritageTransport, LLC.  At the time of the pick-up the Heritage Transport driver was delayed approximately 2 hours while the customer pumped water from the box.  Once the pumping was complete the material appeared to be dry and in proper condition for transportation. The roll-off box was transported to the Heritage Transport, LLC 10-day in Indianapolis, IN and arrived on March 16, 2011.  The box was dropped in the 10-Day without any incident or release of materials on March 16, 2011. On March 23, 2011 an operator from Heritage Environmental Services began to load the roll-off box onto his truck.  As the box was being loaded onto the truck material began coming out of the top of the box onto the ground in the Heritage Transport, LLC 10-Day lot. Approximately 15 pounds of RQ, NA3077, HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S., 9, PGIII, (NICKEL, CHROMIUM), (F006) was released from the roll-off box.  Heritage Transport personnel were contacted to respond to the release.  Oil dry was applied to the affected area to ensure that no material made it into the sewer system or soil.  The material was scooped up along with the oil dry and placed in another roll-off box of the same waste, from the same generator, and then disposed of properly.
column169: Personnel from Heritage Environmental Services will work with the customer to discuss possible changes for transporting this waste.  Heritage Environmental Services and Heritage Transport has in place already a system to ensure that if roll-off boxes are delivered are not dropped in the 10-Day if moisture is present at the time of sampling.  If moisture is present the box will be placed in a containment area and unloaded at that time.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Passing yard job reported ECLX 17001, load, Potassium Hydroxide, Solution, found leaking from bottom outlet valve. Dripping about 30 drips per minute. Car was isolated to old intermodal ramp track and blue flagged by car department for emergency response. Qualified hazmat responder, Hazmat Response, Inc., was mobilized. Investigation found the flange gasket connection of the bottom outlet valeve to the tank shell leaking. Attempts were made to tighten this connection, but it was found tool tight. The tank car was off loaded to highway cargo tanks and lading was delivered via rubber tire mode. The bottom outlet valve was removed by the shipper and repairs were made to the gasket connection. The shipper performed successful qualified leak test. The car was then home shopped for follow up analysis.     F5800 Report Notes:  Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was required to facilitate data acceptance by defective PHMSA DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required for two reasons:   (1)because the shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and   (2)because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field which use the same units of measure as found in the capacity field.   KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

ON MARCH 12, 2011 CLINT JONES WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOAD OF ACID FROM FMI MIAMI. AT 14:59 MIKE KING IN DISPATCH RECEIVED A CALL FROM BRICE MARES, FMI ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, SAYING THEY DISCOVERED A TRUCK LEAKING ACID HAD LEFT THE PROPERTY AND ASKED IF WE COULD CALL OUR DRIVER IN TRUCK 852 TO SEE IF IT WA LEAKING. MIKE CALLED CLINT AND ASKED HIM TO PULL OVER AND CHECK. CLINT PULLED OVER APPROXIMATELY 8 MILES WEST OF SUPERIOR AND DISCOVERED HE DID INDEED HAVE A LEAK. MIKE CALLED BRICE AND INFORMED HIM WE HAD A LEAK, THEN NOTIFIED VICTOR BRUZEE, CTI FACILITY MANAGER AND JOSEPH BLENLEK, DIRECTOR OF HEALTH AND SAFETY. MIKE ALSO CALLED CARL TEFFL AT THE SAFFORD SHOP AND LET HIM KNOW WE WERE GOING TO NEED HIS ASSISTANCE IN CLEANING UP THE SPILL. CARL WAS DISPATHCED TO MEET CLINT AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL AROUND THE TRUCK. BRICE THEN CALLED BAK AND LET MIKE KNOW THAT WE HAD A 2' X 2' SPILL AT AN INTERSECTION IN MIAMI. MIKE CALLED CITRO AND LET HIM KNOW ABOUT THE SPILL IN MIAMI, VICTOR TOLD MIKE TO NOTIFY THE POLICE IN MIAMI ABOUT THE SPILL. MIKE CALLED MIAMI PD AND THEY INFORMED HIM TO NOTIFY THE GILA COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPT. MIKE THEN CONTACTED THE GILA COUNTY SHERRIF'S DEPARTMENT AND THEY SAID THEY WOULD NOTIFY THE TRI CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL. THEY ALSO SAID WE HAD TO CONTACT DPS BECAUSE THE SPILL WAS ON ROUTE 60. MIKE CONTACTED DPS AND THEY SAID THEY WOULD CONTACT THE OFFICERS IN THE AREA. MIKE THEN CONTACTED BRICE ANS USAN TOLER, FMI SENIOR ANALYST, AND LET THEM KNOW WHAT HAPPENING.  IT WAS DETERMINED FROM CLINTS SCALE TICKETS FROM FMI MIAMI AND FMI GADAD THAT 80 LBS OF SULFURIC ACID HAD SPILLED ON THE GROUND. THIS IS BELOW THE 1000 LB RQ THRESHOLD AND THEREFORE DOES NOT MEET NRC NOTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS UNDER 302.3(1)  NOTE:  MR. DANE WAS PERMANENTLY BANNED FROM FMI PROPERTY. BECAUSE OF THIS HE WAS UNABLE TO COMPLETE HIS DUTIES FOR CTI AND WAS TERMED ON 3/15/2011
column169: 1. THE DOME LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. WHEN CLINT CLIMBED UP TO CHECK THE DOME HE NOTICED THE LID HAD BEEN SEALED TOO FAR TO THE LEFT AND ACID WAS LEAKING FROM THE RIGHT SIDE.  2. CLINT DID NOT FOLLOW SOP'S. HE DID NOT CHECK HIS TRAILER BEFORE SCALING OUT TO LEAVE THE PROPERTY.   CLINT HAS BEEN COUNSELED ON THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING SOP'S AND THAT FOLLOWING SOP'S MAY HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL FROM TAKING PLACE.

column169: AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, WE REVIEWD OUT FILLING PROCEDURES FOR THE PROPANE DELIVERY TRUCKS (BOBTAILS). THE PROCEDURE WAS WRITTEN AND ALL BOBTAIL DRIVERS WERE GIVEN A COPY, REQUIRED TO READ AND SIGN ATTESTING THAT THEY UNDERSTAND THE PROCEDURES. ALL BOBTAILS THAT DID NOT HAVE THE SCREENED FILLING ADAPTOR WERE OUTFITTED WITH THEM, SO THAT OUR ENTIRE BOBTAIL FLEET HAS THIS PROTECTION AGAINST FOREIGN OBJECTS. WE ALSO UPDATED THE BULK PLANTS AS WELL.

column168: Container EMHU 684582, located in the Global Two Yard in Northlake, IL, was reported to be releasing an unknown liquid.  Investigation found the release was spearmint oil coming from one of the stainless steel totes in the container.  The container held eight totes and the lid on the right front tote was not secured on the tote, allowing product to splash out of the tote.  The tote was secured and the shipper arranged for the container to be cleaned prior to being released.

column168: The loaded transport vehicle was traveling westbound on Txas FM887, approximately 5 miles west of Gillett, TX.  The vehicle entered a curve in the roadway at a speed in excess of roadway and lighting conditions and overturned.  As a result of the overturned vehicle, a release of 162 barrels of petroleum crude oil occurred due to a split in the shell of the transport trailer unit caused by the rollover.  Spill response equipment and trained personnel were immediately deployed to the scene in a timely manner to respond to the release of material.
column169: The outcome of the incident investigation, once complete, will be shared with all management team members and driver personnel.  Company policies and procedures are currently being reviewed, and as determined necessary, will be revised to improve incident prevention and response measures.  In addition, driver personnel will receive additioanl training with regard to large vehicle speed management and defensive driving best practices.
